<span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">This fragment from the Kizil Grottoes provides a glimpse of the rich tradition of <span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">Central Asian<span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none"> Buddhist painting. Kizil was an important <span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">Buddhist<span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none"> centre. It lay on the <span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">northern silk route<span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">, used by pilgrim monks <span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">on their way to visit holy sites in India<span lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US" data-contrast="none">, and its 236 rock cut caves were richly decorated with paintings.&nbsp;&nbsp;


